From: wpp@marie.physik.tu-berlin.de (Kai Petzke)
Subject: Re: Pentium, or better: 586
Date: 15 Oct 1993 23:31:02 GMT

In <CExBv3.D6@mts.mivj.ca.us> rpao@mts.mivj.ca.us (Roger C. Pao) writes:

>wpp@marie.physik.tu-berlin.de (Kai Petzke) writes:

>>Quite regularly, people ask questions about Linux on 586, or Pentium.
>>This is quite natural, the 586 is probably the most powerfull chip,
>>on which Linux runs on at the moment (this may change with an
>>ALPHA port :-)

>I heard from a co-worker who was visiting Intel that in a comparison of
>Windows NT running on Pentium and the DEC Alpha, the Pentium system was
>much faster.  3D rendering was smooth vs. choppy.

I read the opposite in a German PC magazine (sorry, I do not remember
which one).  The 586 was only a bit faster then the 486, and the Alpha
was ways ahead.

There are two modes, in which the ALPHA can run NT applications:

- One by emulating an 386.  This mode is slow.  However, library calls are
  still done in ALPHA mode, so you won't see the low speed on a word processor
  (which spends most of the time calling graphical libraries), but you will
  see it in a programme, that does extensive calculations (like 3D rendering).

- Or real ALPHA mode, if the applications were compiled for this.  This mode
  ist fast.

>Note the test was setup by Intel, and the DEC Alpha Windows NT is in
>Beta.  Who can vouch for the validity of the test?

You are totally right.  I would not buy NT anyways, whether on 586 or ALPHA.

--
Kai
wpp@marie.physik.tu-berlin.de
Advertisement by Microsoft in a well-known German magazine:
        If you don't like our programmes, than make your own ones.
However, they expect you to use Microsoft products for this -:)

