From: kevin@frobozz.sccsi.com (Kevin Brown)
Subject: Re: The %&#$@ speaks again -or- An apology
Date: Fri, 15 Oct 1993 21:44:48 GMT

In article <1993Oct14.164224.14104@mulvey.com> rich@mulvey.com writes:
>Kevin Brown (kevin@frobozz.sccsi.com) wrote:
>: In article <1993Oct13.162636.8794@mulvey.com> rich@mulvey.com writes:

[on the FAQ]

>: >   So what if it's long?  Even the skimpy MS-DOS manuals that come with
>: >Our Favorite OS are longer.  
>
>: You should know better than this.  Most people don't learn DOS or any other
>: such thing from the manual.  They learn how to use the computer by asking
>: others who already know.  This is precisely why users like the Macintosh
>: so much: they don't *have* to pick up the manual, and they don't usually
>: have to ask someone else for the answers.  The Macintosh is "intuitive",
>: which is just another way of saying that it has enough similarities with
>: things that most people have experience with (e.g., the trashcan) that it
>: works the way people would *expect* it to work.
>
>   I disagree.  ( Surprising, eh? ;-)

Yeah.  You're not supposed to do that.  :-)

> Most people that I've encountered in
>my professional and personal life typically try using the machine, get
>fed up when they can't figure out what to do, and then go look at the
>manual.  Eventually, they learn that it's a good idea to at least *skim*
>the manual before trying something new, at least if they value their
>time.

Which is all well and good, and probably true to a large degree.  However:
Linux is usually not a prepackaged thing to the extent that other commercial
software is.  There is often *no* manual to look at to begin with, unless
the FAQ comes prepackaged with the various distributions that are available.

And even so, most people would prefer to *not* have to look in the manual.
They do so as a last resort, which is my point.  Rather, they will ask
someone *first*, not *last*.

Now, the net represents a huge community of people to ask.  Guess what
most people end up doing?  Right: they ask before reading the manual.

>: My own experience indicates that the "index" (which is no such thing,
>: really, but is rather a table of contents) is a poor way of locating the
>: information I'm looking for when I'm searching for the answer to a question.
>: I get much better results searching the actual text for certain keywords
>: and then examining the text surrounding the keywords.
>
>   Which is *precisely* the right way to do it.  2 minutes of instruction
>on how to use grep, and you're home free.

This is true *only* if the user in question already has a working system.
If they don't, then they lose, right?

>: >Not necessarily.  A person who has the ability to use an editor to post
>: >a stupid question is likely to know that you can search for text, as
>: >well.
>
>: I don't think so, given what I've seen of most users.  But since most users
>: I've seen don't even know what Unix is, I can't really comment on this.
>
>   I find it highly unlikely that the people who are asking the silly
>questions in *this* group don't know what Unix is.  

Well, my point is that if there isn't a substantive difference between
users who know what Unix is and those who don't, then my comments apply.
If someone knows what Unix is, does this imply that they are likely to
be significantly more knowledgable about computers (and thus more likely
to know how things work) than someone who doesn't know about Unix?

>Well, I have to 
>qualify that - I've seen a couple of posts asking more or less "what is
>Unix?"  But that's still irrelevent when the person obviously has *some*
>access to an editor on ANY platform to make the post in the first
>place.

You are aware, of course, that editors are invoked automatically by the
newsreaders, and that the ability to post news does not imply the knowledge
necessary to invoke the editor?  Even so, it says nothing about the person's
ability to *use* the editor, save for the ability to type in text.

However, I think I'll have to concede this point at least in part, because
most people who post have .signatures.  :-)

>: But I will say this: even among the students in my own computer science
>: department, only a handful of them know how to use the search facilities
>: of the editor.  Most of them search by "hand".
>
>   Quite honestly, that doesn't say a heck of a lot for the quality of your
>student body.  

No kidding.  :-(

>If they're supposed to be learning how to be professional
>programmer, SE's, or MIS people, they should seriously reconsider how they're
>spending their money if they don't use the most basic tools of their
>profession.

Well, modern times have brought us mouse-based editors with menus and the
like, and *these* are what people seem to use these days.  Thus, the ability
to search for something is obvious because it exists in the menu.  I was,
however, referring to the editor on the VAX (under VMS), which is something
that few people really know how to use.

Now ask yourself how many people know how to use vi, or emacs, or any other
editor for which help isn't available or for which it isn't obvious how to
get to the help facility.

>: Most people are not "self-starters" to the extent that computer experts
>: typically are, at least when it comes to technology.  When faced with a
>: computer or *any* other piece of technology they are unfamiliar with, most
>: people will stop dead in their tracks unless they have someone to ask about
>: the problem.  Many of them won't even *think* of reading the manual.  If
>: you don't believe me, take a look at how few people know how to program
>: their VCR, and of those who do know, take a look at how few of them found
>: out by reading the manual rather than having someone *show* them.
>
>   All well and good, but when the people decide that they want to start
>using/asking about Linux, they're coming to play in our backyard, and we
>have our own rules to play by.  If they can't deal with that, they should
>leave, just like in any other profession/hobby/avocation.

Sorry, but it doesn't work that way.  :-)  Basically, USENET is an anarchy,
and people can do whatever they want.  That, of course, includes flaming
newbies for posting inappropriate material.  :-)

And you fail to really grasp my point:  people are people, and they're going
to behave the way they do regardless of how you might like to change it.
This is something we must deal with (one way or another) regardless of
whether we're on the net or in face-to-face conversation with them.

>: >And when I *do*
>: >encounter something that I'm lost about, then I post a *useful and
>: >complete* description of my problem, what I've tried, and what I think
>: >may be wrong.  
>
>: Yup.  But you, I, and most of us who tend to do this are essentially experts
>: at working with technology.  We know the ups and downs and know that the key
>: to understanding technology is learning about the principles behind the
>: technology.  We know what kinds of questions to ask and the level of detail
>: necessary because we've dealt with *answering* questions like that before.
>: How many can claim this?  Not many, given what I've seen.
>
>   I've always partial to the (over)used example of the guy who brings his
>car to the mechanic and says,"It's broken.  Fix it."  Do most people do
>this?  No.  Even if they haven't the slightest clue about how a car works.

And why is that?  Because they did it a few times and the mechanic asked
them to describe the symptoms.  The mechanic did *not* flame them into
oblivion for not knowing anything about cars (such a mechanic wouldn't get
a lot of repeat business).  Eventually, the person catches on to the fact
that when their car breaks, they have to tell the mechanic what the symptoms
are.

>But for some reason, when they get on USENET, they decide that everyone 
>else has ESP and a direct video link to their desk so we can see what
>they're doing.  Sorry, but it just doesn't cut it.  

Yeah, but the response of a lot (but not all) of people here on USENET,
and c.o.l.d. in particular, is *not* to ask them about the symptoms, but
to flame them for asking a stupid/inappropriate question!  People aren't
going to generalize their experience with cars to computers, because
computers are perceived to be *different* (even though we really know that
dealing with each is much the same in an abstract sense).

>: >The morons who post things like "My smail doesn't work.
>: >What do I do?" have no place in any of these groups, or in society as
>: >a whole, for that matter, until they learn how to not waste other
>: >people's time.  
>
>: Welcome to the real world.  :-) :-)
>
>   Haven't we had this conversation before, in another thread?  :-)

I have no idea.  No comment.  :-) :-)

>: Seriously, most people won't bother to learn more than they have to in
>: order to get the job done.  If they did, then *everyone* would be
>: technologically literate.
>
>   I'm not asking them to learn the slightest thing about computers.  I'm
>asking them to use their brains in a very general manner.  Specifically,
>but treating a post on USENET the same way they would treat a conversation
>with a live person.

But they *are* treating it the same way as they would a live conversation.
The difference isn't with the *initiation*, it's with the *response*.  In
particular, in a live conversation you *would not* flame them into oblivion.
You'd ask them what the symptoms are and they'd tell you.  Eventually, they
would have the answer to their question, if it were a live conversation.

But here on USENET, the respondees are flaming the initiators into oblivion.
In short, it is *they* who are conversing differently than in real life.

>: Wrong.  Flaming the hell out of them is a useful memory-enhancing technique
>: that makes them think twice before asking *any* question of the people they
>: asked before.  You're ignoring a very basic principle of education: a question
>: is *never* a stupid question from the point of view of the person asking the
>: question.  Very few people like to look stupid in front of other people.  If
>: they're asking a question, it's because they DON'T KNOW HOW to get the answer
>: for themselves, or at the very least are very uncomfortable and uncertain
>: about it.
>
>   Ahhhhh.... but you've just noted that it starts them thinking.  

Yeah, but it starts them thinking about the wrong thing.  Do you seriously
believe that as a result of one or several flames that they start thinking
about looking in the manual?  Nope.  What they do is start thinking that
(a) they're not going to ask *these* bozos any more questions, and (b) they'll
have to ask someone else who might be more receptive to such a question.

>That's 
>the *MOST* important first step.  The qualification about looking stupid
>is invalid when it comes to USENET.  We're using the most effective
>means of anonymous communication ever devised.  

Bzzzt.  Thank you for playing.  Yeah, it's "anonymous" but peers are peers
no matter what the communication medium, and people feel stupid if it's
pointed out to them that what they're doing is stupid no matter *how* it's
pointed out.  People don't feel stupid because *others* think of them as
being stupid, they feel stupid because they regard *themselves* that way
(at least with respect to whatever action you're talking about) as a result
of what others tell them.

>I'm a great believer in the
>effectiveness of making people uncomfortable to force them into
>certain socially acceptable behavior patterns.  Just think of how many more
>kids would be in trouble if they weren't "uncomfortable" using drugs,
>drinking to excess, and having sex in front of their parents.  It works
>the same way for adults, as well.

Sorry, but for this particular case this doesn't apply.  Discomfort only
works to *discourage* a certain behavior, and the only way it can possibly
encourage another *specific* kind of behavior is if that other behavior is
the only other available choice.  That's *not* the case here.  If you flame
someone into oblivion over posting a question to c.o.l.d., there are a
number of things they can do:  they can give more details and post the
question again (not likely, but possible), they can ask their question on
a different (but still inappropriate) newsgroup, they can ask someone in
person (or call someone), they can send mail to someone they've seen being
reasonably receptive to such questions, or they *might* do what you want
them to do and check the FAQ (and (*this* assumes that they have access
to it to begin with).

Either way, it's quite likely that such a newbie will *not* bother to ask
*any* question of people in c.o.l.d. again, EVEN IF THE QUESTION IS VALID, 
because their experience with people in c.o.l.d. will be that the people
there are intolerant, holier-than-thou types who have "better" things to
do than to answer questions.

Is that really the effect you're shooting for?


-- 
